11:57.450 --> 12:01.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this increasing adoption of
suffocation or hanging as a
suicide method by both males

12:01.354 --> 12:04.657 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and females, and that is
a highly lethal method.

12:04.657 --> 12:07.226 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And compare
that to guns, which is probably
still the number one...

12:07.226 --> 12:08.294 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

12:08.294 --> 12:12.832 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KATHERINE HEMPSTEAD: Guns is the
most lethal means of suicide.

12:12.832 --> 12:17.303 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And guns is the most important
method for males. But we saw for
both males and females

12:17.303 --> 12:21.074 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
an increase in suffocation
as a share of suicides.

12:21.074 --> 12:25.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: One of the
things to keep in mind that, are
suicides unreported, because

12:25.178 --> 12:28.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it looks like these CDC numbers
would have to come with the
coroner's said suicide on

12:28.081 --> 12:30.383 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the death certificate?

12:30.383 --> 12:36.155 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHERINE HEMPSTEAD: There is
probably some underreporting of
suicides, but I think that,

12:36.155 --> 12:40.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
over this time period, I don't
believe this is any kind of a
data artifact.

12:40.493 --> 12:44.097 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I don't think that
underreporting has been a huge
part of the problem or that's
changed

12:44.097 --> 12:48.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a lot over the last 15 years, so
I think this is a real trend in
suicide.

12:48.267 --> 12:51.404 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And is there
any way to capture, well,
unsuccessful suicides, attempts

12:51.404 --> 12:52.639 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or hospitalizations?

12:52.639 --> 12:55.975 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KATHERINE HEMPSTEAD: Oh, yes.

12:55.975 --> 13:00.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When people attempt suicide,
many times, it results in an
emergency room admission, so

13:00.380 --> 13:04.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we do have a lot of data on
nonfatal attempts. A lot of
those attempts are done with
poisoning.

13:04.550 --> 13:08.021 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's probably the most common
method for nonfatal attempts.

13:08.021 --> 13:12.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we do find that females vs.
males, as we already mentioned,
have a higher ratio

13:12.992 --> 13:17.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of non-fatal to fatal attempts,
because they tend to use less
lethal methods. And we also

13:17.463 --> 13:21.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
see, for certain age groups,
like younger groups in
particular, there's more
nonfatal

13:21.534 --> 13:23.169 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
attempts.

13:23.169 --> 13:25.872 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is that
because younger people are doing
this more impulsively than

13:25.872 --> 13:27.907 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
older people?

13:27.907 --> 13:32.445 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHERINE HEMPSTEAD: Well, there
is -- yes, there is a lot of
evidence that, among younger

13:32.445 --> 13:36.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people, suicidal behavior,
whether it's fatal or nonfatal,
has a more impulsive
origination.

13:36.816 --> 13:41.187 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it could be a response --
and this is I think something
that is true especially

13:41.187 --> 13:45.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for young males -- response to
some kind of adverse event,
maybe a relationship problem,

13:45.992 --> 13:51.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a fight with an authority
figure, problem with parents,
maybe a minor legal infraction.

13:51.998 --> 13:57.470 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So we see a lot of suicides --
suicide attempts and completed
suicides for younger people

13:57.470 --> 14:01.274 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that -- especially males, that
are the result of sort of recent
crises that sort of precipitate

14:01.274 --> 14:03.810 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
impulsive self-injury.

14:03.810 --> 14:08.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Are there
large-scale patterns that you
can say are maybe attributed to
the

14:08.414 --> 14:13.186 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
economy or the great recession
that we just went through, or
when people are down in the

14:13.186 --> 14:15.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
dumps, they have lost their
fortunes, they have lost
everything? Are these the times

14:15.354 --> 14:18.191 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
where we see suicides pick up?

14:18.191 --> 14:21.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHERINE HEMPSTEAD: Well,
that's really the thing that we
focused on when we looked at

14:21.127 --> 14:26.899 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the middle-aged. And we did look
to see, could we associate any
particular kind of circumstances

14:26.899 --> 14:29.836 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to this rising rate of suicide
among the middle-aged?

14:29.836 --> 14:36.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And sure enough we did see an
increasing reference to things
like job problems, personal
finance

14:36.375 --> 14:41.414 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
issues, foreclosures,
bankruptcies, things that really
accelerated during this time of

14:41.414 --> 14:45.118 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the recession, but we see that
those trends are kind of
persisting even when a lot of

14:45.118 --> 14:48.054 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people feel like the economy's
recovered quite a bit, but maybe
those improvements aren't

14:48.054 --> 14:51.624 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
being felt by everybody.

14:51.624 --> 14:55.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the middle-aged, I think,
are particularly vulnerable to
those kinds of pressures,
because

14:55.862 --> 14:59.999 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they are breadwinners, they have
dependents, their own retirement
might not be secure,

14:59.999 --> 15:04.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they might have children to put
through college. So I think they
can be particularly affected

15:04.170 --> 15:07.206 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
by those kinds of
economic problems.

15:07.206 --> 15:10.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Are there
reasons that explain what is
happening with younger people,
teenagers?

15:10.343 --> 15:14.881 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I know there are small cohorts
from 13 to 18 and so forth, the
way that the CDC breaks

15:14.881 --> 15:17.984 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out the numbers, but when you
look at overall number, it's
increasing.

15:17.984 --> 15:22.688 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHERINE HEMPSTEAD: Well,
that's particularly troubling,
because it's a little bit harder

15:22.688 --> 15:29.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to pin those kinds of increases
to the broader kinds of
economic, you know, pocketbook
issues

15:29.028 --> 15:31.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that are more -- you would think
have more of an impact on older
people that had those

15:31.998 --> 15:34.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
kinds of responsibilities.

15:34.300 --> 15:37.436 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think that is something
that people are very concerned
about and want to understand

15:37.436 --> 15:39.639 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
better, what are
those motivations?

15:39.639 --> 15:43.309 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And is
there a contagion effect?

15:43.309 --> 15:48.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHERINE HEMPSTEAD: You know,
some people have talked about
that.

15:48.347 --> 15:54.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, I think that is
extremely difficult to have
really rigorous evidence to
either

15:54.253 --> 15:58.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
support or refute the idea of
some kind of contagion,
particularly to say that that
would

15:58.658 --> 16:04.230 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
account for a large share of
suicide, but I do think that
there are sort of waxes and

16:04.230 --> 16:08.734 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
wanes and times in which suicide
may come to seem more sort of
culturally acceptable

16:08.734 --> 16:12.905 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or a more popular way to talk
about a response to problems.

16:12.905 --> 16:19.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this can sort of kind of
rise and fall over time and go
in and out of favor with

16:19.011 --> 16:22.415 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
certain groups. And I think
adolescents can be susceptible
to that kind of language and

16:22.415 --> 16:24.450 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
imagery.

16:24.450 --> 16:25.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Katherine Hempstead from the
Robert Wood Johnson Foundation,
thanks

16:25.518 --> 16:27.019 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
so much.

16:27.019 --> 16:35.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHERINE HEMPSTEAD: Sure. It's
a pleasure. Thanks for having me
on.

16:35.561 --> 16:46.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Virginia Governor
Terry McAuliffe signed a
sweeping order today to restore
voting

16:46.439 --> 16:52.478 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rights to more than 200,000
convicted felons after their
release from prison.

16:52.478 --> 16:56.482 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Republicans in the commonwealth
quickly accused the governor of
abusing his executive power

16:56.482 --> 17:00.152 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to help Democrat Hillary Clinton
win a battleground state.

17:00.152 --> 17:02.255 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Governor McAuliffe joins
me now from Richmond.

17:02.255 --> 17:05.091 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Governor, welcome.

17:05.091 --> 17:08.527 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why the decision to overturn
something that's been in place
in your state since the Civil

17:08.527 --> 17:10.196 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
War?

17:10.196 --> 17:12.798 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GOV. TERRY MCAULIFFE (D),
Virginia: Well, let's be honest.
We have had a bad history

17:12.798 --> 17:18.771 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
here on voting rights in
Virginia. 1901, 1902, they put
in the poll tax. They put in
literacy

17:18.771 --> 17:22.642 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tests. And they had a horrible
disenfranchisement for felons.

17:22.642 --> 17:30.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what I did today was to
erase 114, 115 years of a
really, really repressive tactic

17:30.316 --> 17:33.486 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
used to deprive people
their right to vote.

17:33.486 --> 17:38.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You included
convicted felons who were
accused of violent crimes,
murder,

17:38.791 --> 17:41.594 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
rape. You didn't make any
exceptions. Why not?

17:41.594 --> 17:44.363 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
GOV. TERRY MCAULIFFE:
No. Why should I?

17:44.363 --> 17:49.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Once you have served your time,
once you have paid your debt to
society, the judge, jury

17:49.802 --> 17:53.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have determined what your
sentence would be, once you
complete that, why should you
not

17:53.272 --> 17:55.741 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be back in?

17:55.741 --> 17:59.745 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When these people, even if they
have committed heinous crimes,
but once they have finished

17:59.745 --> 18:05.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
serving their sentence, they go
back to their communities, they
get jobs, they have family

18:05.418 --> 18:09.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
members. You want them, Judy --
I want everybody back getting a
job. I want them paying taxes.

18:09.221 --> 18:11.123 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I want them feeling
good about themselves.

18:11.123 --> 18:13.659 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You have paid your
debt to society.

18:13.659 --> 18:18.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: As you just
heard, the Republican Party in
your state is questioning why
you

18:18.998 --> 18:27.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
did this blanket change in the
law, in what was the law for so
long, and they're saying

18:27.406 --> 18:30.743 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it's an example of political
opportunism, that you have got
this election coming up,

18:30.743 --> 18:32.912 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and that explains
the timing of it.

18:32.912 --> 18:36.048 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GOV. TERRY MCAULIFFE: Well,
Judy, let me be very clear.

18:36.048 --> 18:40.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If I were to do it for political
purposes, I would have done it
last year, before my

18:40.453 --> 18:46.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
entire 140-member of the General
Assembly. As you know, you
follow the news, I worked

18:46.425 --> 18:50.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very hard to win one Senate seat
to get control of the Senate. If
I were to do this for political

18:50.429 --> 18:53.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
purposes, I would have
done it last year.

18:53.566 --> 18:56.736 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
First of all, let me be very
clear. Hillary Clinton doesn't
need this. She is going to

18:56.736 --> 19:00.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
win Virginia. She is going to
beat Donald Trump. So, put the
politics aside. And it's

19:00.873 --> 19:06.312 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
really unfortunate these
Republicans always default to
partisan politics.

19:06.312 --> 19:12.284 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This was, morally, the right
thing to do. This was about
letting people who have already

19:12.284 --> 19:16.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
served their sentence, they are
done with probation, back in as
full citizens of our

19:16.756 --> 19:19.592 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
society. That's
what we should do.

19:19.592 --> 19:23.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Governor --
Governor, let me ask you about
another argument that's made,

19:23.396 --> 19:26.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and this is a conservative
argument. The gentleman we
spoke, his name Roger Clegg, he
heads the

19:26.732 --> 19:29.869 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Center for Equal Opportunity.

19:29.869 --> 19:35.674 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He said re-enfranchisement,
letting people vote again, it
makes sense on a case-by-case

19:35.674 --> 19:41.047 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
basis, once a person can show
that they have actually turned
over a new leaf, changed their

19:41.047 --> 19:46.452 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
behavior. But he said, when you
grant this sort of right to vote
to everybody, you are

19:46.452 --> 19:51.390 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
not allowing the -- each
individual to show whether they
have respect for the law.

19:51.390 --> 19:55.661 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he makes the point. He says,
you can't demand the right --
what basically you're

19:55.661 --> 20:01.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
doing is giving the right to
vote to people who would be then
determining other people's

20:01.333 --> 20:03.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
votes, other people's laws,
which is what you do when you
vote.

20:03.936 --> 20:07.873 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
GOV. TERRY MCAULIFFE:
Oh, Judy, that's silly.

20:07.873 --> 20:14.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
First of all, let me be clear.
I'm restoring voting rights. I'm
not giving people back

20:14.046 --> 20:20.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
gun rights. I'm not commuting
anyone's sentence. I am giving
people who are now -- have
served

20:20.453 --> 20:24.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- they have paid their debt to
society. That debt was
determined by a judge and a
jury.

20:24.590 --> 20:27.460 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And they said, this is
the debt to pay back.

20:27.460 --> 20:32.164 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Once you have done that, I'm
saying you can come back and be
part of society. You can

20:32.164 --> 20:35.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
go back, and you can have a job,
you can buy a home, you can do
everything else. I want

20:35.568 --> 20:38.537 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
you feeling good about
yourself and voting.

20:38.537 --> 20:43.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, we have a difference of
opinion. I was proud to do this
today. It was morally the

20:43.375 --> 20:48.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
right thing to do. I have the
full legal authority under the
Constitution to do it, the legal

20:48.214 --> 20:51.417 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
authority. I have the moral
authority. And I did it.

20:51.417 --> 20:54.487 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Just finally,
Governor, you have said today, I
believe, that you want

20:54.487 --> 20:59.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to encourage these individuals
to register and vote. How are
you going to do that?

20:59.091 --> 21:02.161 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GOV. TERRY MCAULIFFE: Well, I
think by coming on your show,
and I think we're going to see

21:02.161 --> 21:05.397 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
an awful lot of press
that came off it today.

21:05.397 --> 21:08.501 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Judy, if you could have been
with me -- and we didn't tell
anybody what we were doing

21:08.501 --> 21:12.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
today. We invited a lot of folks
from restoration of rights
community, because I have done a

21:12.471 --> 21:16.976 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
lot of these events. They didn't
know. When I announced what I
was doing today, the folks

21:16.976 --> 21:21.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who came up to me and said,
Governor, I haven't voted in 20
years or 30 -- there were
mothers

21:21.547 --> 21:25.918 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
crying. There were fathers
crying. There were sons and
daughters crying.

21:25.918 --> 21:30.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was a great feeling. I
restored the rights a couple
months ago of Bobby Blevins. He
had

21:30.489 --> 21:36.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not voted for 60 years. He made
a mistake when he was 19 years
old. He is now 79. And

21:36.195 --> 21:40.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to see this grown man standing
next to me weeping in tears when
I signed the order,

21:40.933 --> 21:45.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and he got to vote -- and then
he called me after he got to
vote in the last election.

21:45.638 --> 21:52.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know what? That's what
leadership is all about. As
governor, my job is to grow an
economy.

21:52.178 --> 21:57.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My job is to make sure that
everybody can enjoy a great
life. What I did today was
morally

21:57.616 --> 22:01.987 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the right thing to do. I gave
people back their voting rights,
plain and simple.

22:01.987 --> 22:06.225 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You served your time, come on
in, be part of the Virginia
economy. Be part of our family.

22:06.225 --> 22:09.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you can't do it if you treat
people like second-class
citizens.

22:09.995 --> 22:12.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Governor Terry
McAuliffe of the Commonwealth of
Virginia, we thank you

22:12.531 --> 22:14.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
very much.

22:14.700 --> 22:22.107 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GOV. TERRY MCAULIFFE: Thank you.

22:22.107 --> 22:29.281 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Thank you.

22:29.281 --> 22:32.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And now to the analysis of
Shields and Brooks. That's
syndicated columnist Mark
Shields and

22:32.451 --> 22:34.553 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
New York Times columnist
David Brooks.

22:34.553 --> 22:37.156 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Welcome to you, gentlemen.

22:37.156 --> 22:43.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we just heard, David, from
Governor McAuliffe of Virginia.
He has decided, as we just
heard,

22:43.395 --> 22:50.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to allow 200 -- in effect,
200,000 ex-felons, people who
served their time for a felony

22:50.569 --> 22:53.239 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
crime, to vote. What
do you make of it?

22:53.239 --> 22:57.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes, I would love
to see the ideological breakdown
of ex-felons.

22:57.076 --> 23:00.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think it's the right thing
to do. I have never quite
understood. You know, you're

23:00.546 --> 23:07.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
assigned a cost you have to pay
for committing a crime or even a
felony. You do your time,

23:07.586 --> 23:10.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you do your parole, you do your
probation, you should be able to
rejoin society in full

23:10.089 --> 23:12.691 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
measure.

23:12.691 --> 23:15.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of the weird things in our
whole criminal just system is,
we have got people who are

23:15.961 --> 23:21.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
50, and 60, well past what they
call criminal menopause, and
they're perfectly upstanding

23:21.066 --> 23:23.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
citizens, and they're not the
person they were at 19, and yet
we continue to punish

23:23.969 --> 23:25.904 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
them.

23:25.904 --> 23:27.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And whether they're in jail, we
should be more lenient on them.
If they're out, we should

23:27.606 --> 23:28.440 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
make them full citizens.

23:28.440 --> 23:29.541 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark?

23:29.541 --> 23:31.877 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: I agree.

23:31.877 --> 23:37.650 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I thought Terry McAuliffe,
who is accused of being a super
salesman, a huckster, whatever,

23:37.650 --> 23:42.855 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I thought he was quite
persuasive in his case that,
especially in Virginia's long
history

23:42.855 --> 23:48.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of denying the vote to people
persistently, as part of
governmental policy, given the

23:48.260 --> 23:50.863 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
historical record.

23:50.863 --> 23:56.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And once a person has paid his
or her debt to society and is
off parole, I mean, why

23:56.969 --> 24:02.107 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not? And don't we want them to
become part of society again and
the community?

24:02.107 --> 24:05.311 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I mean,
apparently, there are more and
more states that are doing this.

24:05.311 --> 24:05.978 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And a lot of the questions...

24:05.978 --> 24:07.613 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

24:07.613 --> 24:11.583 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes, and a lot of
red states, too, so, you know,
the whole political question.

24:11.583 --> 24:15.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So let's move too
the presidential contest and
surprise -- David, I want to ask

24:15.587 --> 24:18.190 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
