happening to the environment
and the impact of development.

41:40.231 --> 41:46.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That tension is playing out here
in Alabama, with one of the
country's preeminent naturalists

41:46.037 --> 41:50.775 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
calling for the creation of a
new protected area to cover a
critical waterway.

41:50.775 --> 41:53.511 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has our report.

41:53.511 --> 42:00.017 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The Mobile-Tensaw
Delta, where five rivers meet in
Southern Alabama to drain

42:00.017 --> 42:07.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into the Gulf of Mexico, more
than 200,000 acres of bog,
marsh, swampland and floodplain,

42:07.658 --> 42:12.029 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
it's one of the most
biologically diverse places in
North America, home to scores of

42:12.029 --> 42:17.001 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
species of flowers, birds,
fish, turtles, and more.

42:17.001 --> 42:22.106 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
E.O. WILSON, Biologist: And
there are a tremendous variety
of plants and animals in it.

42:22.106 --> 42:27.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It's also the
childhood playground of Edward
O. Wilson, where he searched out

42:27.578 --> 42:33.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
snakes and insects, and worked
as a 14-year-old counselor at
nearby Camp Pushmataha.

42:33.151 --> 42:39.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
E.O. WILSON: It was wartime. And
they didn't have any older,
smarter kids to be nature

42:39.157 --> 42:45.830 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
counselor. So, I just simply led
the boys through the whole
summer on expeditions searching

42:45.830 --> 42:52.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and capturing snakes. We built
up a fantastic collection of
different species of snakes.

42:52.437 --> 42:56.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And thus was born the
naturalist, and thus was born
the professor.

42:56.841 --> 43:01.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: One of the
world's best-known professors, a
leading biologist and
naturalist,

43:01.312 --> 43:05.082 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and a two-time Pulitzer
Prize-winning author.

43:05.082 --> 43:11.155 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now 86, Wilson's quest is to
preserve the diversity of life
on the Earth, including

43:11.155 --> 43:14.459 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
here in the delta, where he and
others have been lobbying for
the creation of a new national

43:14.459 --> 43:16.260 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
park.

43:16.260 --> 43:18.963 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BILL FINCH, Botanist: This is
golden club. It's just one of
the beautiful flowers. It's

43:18.963 --> 43:21.732 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
really a peculiar
flower, isn't it?

43:21.732 --> 43:25.069 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Working with
Wilson on the park effort, and
joining us in the Hurricane

43:25.069 --> 43:28.840 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bayou recently, was writer
and botanist Bill Finch.

43:28.840 --> 43:32.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BILL FINCH: It's a beautiful
spring day here on the Gulf
Coast.

43:32.243 --> 43:36.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Among his many
roles, Finch hosts a Sunday
morning call-in radio show

43:36.247 --> 43:40.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in Mobile to talk nature,
gardening and the delta.

43:40.751 --> 43:43.754 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BILL FINCH: We will talk about,
what is the future of this
delta? What is the future of

43:43.754 --> 43:48.793 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mobile Bay? Will it still be
here in a few years for us?

43:48.793 --> 43:54.165 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Working in the
delta's favor, Finch says, is
its sheer size and power. The

43:54.165 --> 43:59.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
water is simply too wild to do
any major building here.
Moreover, the state government
has already

43:59.937 --> 44:05.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
protected tens of thousands of
acres through its Forever Wild
Land Trust, which uses taxes

44:05.276 --> 44:08.546 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on oil drilling to purchase
conservation lands.

44:08.546 --> 44:11.148 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BILL FINCH: We have done great
work protecting this floodplain.

44:11.148 --> 44:11.983 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: In
where we are now?

44:11.983 --> 44:14.051 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BILL FINCH: Where we are now.

44:14.051 --> 44:18.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The land wasn't expensive. It
wasn't hard to purchase. But not
everything lives in the

44:18.222 --> 44:22.994 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
floodplain. And even the turtles
who live here require the dry
land. What we have done

44:22.994 --> 44:29.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a terrible job of is preserving
the areas where people can
develop, the areas that are

44:29.333 --> 44:31.869 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
dryer than this.

44:31.869 --> 44:35.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Finch and Wilson
took us to an area that has been
protected, Splinter

44:35.206 --> 44:36.707 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Hill Bog.

44:36.707 --> 44:40.578 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BILL FINCH: This is a leaf that
is meant to look like a flower.

44:40.578 --> 44:43.881 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Home to
carnivorous flowers like these
pitcher plants, which use decoy

44:43.881 --> 44:46.317 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
flowers to trap their prey.

44:46.317 --> 44:49.921 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BILL FINCH: And the insects
crawl in and can't get back out.

44:49.921 --> 44:54.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The bog also
contains a longleaf pine forest,
which Finch says is vital
habitat

44:54.559 --> 44:57.929 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for bears and other species.

44:57.929 --> 45:04.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But this is a relatively small
area, and Finch's real concern
is development, which, among

45:04.402 --> 45:11.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
other things, replaces soil,
plants and natural water ecology
with concrete and asphalt,
sending

45:11.409 --> 45:17.048 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mud and debris rushing into the
delta, clouding the water and
killing plant and animal life.

45:17.048 --> 45:19.383 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So what do you want to see?
What kind of federal...

45:19.383 --> 45:23.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
BILL FINCH: You know,
there's lots of ways.

45:23.254 --> 45:27.825 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have tried to do it alone as
a state. We have tried to get
some federal money. But

45:27.825 --> 45:32.663 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there's lots of opportunities
for getting more federal support
for what we're doing,

45:32.663 --> 45:37.702 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and for getting federal
attention for one of the most
diverse areas in North America.

45:37.702 --> 45:41.939 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so, you know, the National
Park Service provides some
opportunities for that.

45:41.939 --> 45:46.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In 2013, the
Mobile County Commission
endorsed a plan to study the
impact

45:46.844 --> 45:51.449 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of a national park. But even
that has drawn opposition.

45:51.449 --> 45:55.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: If we give the federal
government the power to protect
the delta, they are subject

45:55.419 --> 45:57.455 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to abusing it.

45:57.455 --> 46:00.891 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MERCERIA LUDGOOD, Mobile County
Commissioner: Didn't grow up
fishing or in boats. And -- but

46:00.891 --> 46:03.828 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
when I became a commissioner,
this was part of my district.

46:03.828 --> 46:08.165 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Merceria Ludgood
is a Mobile county commissioner
who favors the study,

46:08.165 --> 46:12.303 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but knows that many of her
constituents will be wary of
going further.

46:12.303 --> 46:16.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MERCERIA LUDGOOD: You will have
the people on the one side who
don't know anything about

46:16.707 --> 46:21.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the delta, its environmental
implications for quality of life
here. All they see is,

46:21.746 --> 46:22.680 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
we need a job.

46:22.680 --> 46:24.448 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

46:24.448 --> 46:29.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MERCERIA LUDGOOD: And so the
conversation then gets
fractured, and you have the
people

46:29.120 --> 46:32.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who want development, who want
the jobs on one side, and the
environmentalists on the

46:32.423 --> 46:37.528 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
other side. And what we have got
to find is a way to marry that.

46:37.528 --> 46:42.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Opposition in
this deeply conservative state
also comes from suspicions of
any federal

46:42.466 --> 46:46.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
intervention, especially one
that could limit hunting and
fishing, sports popular in the

46:46.437 --> 46:48.139 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
delta.

46:48.139 --> 46:49.774 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS ELLIOTT, Baldwin County
Commissioner: The short answer
for why not a national park

46:49.774 --> 46:52.376 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
here is, it's not necessary.

46:52.376 --> 46:57.114 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Chris Elliott is
a commissioner in Baldwin
County, across from Mobile and

46:57.114 --> 47:00.251 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
home to many new housing and
commercial developments.

47:00.251 --> 47:05.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS ELLIOTT: The people of
South Alabama have traditionally
opposed increased federal

47:05.356 --> 47:10.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
government oversight over our
areas. And we just don't think
it's necessary here in South

47:10.127 --> 47:14.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Alabama. We're doing a fine job
protecting this natural resource
on our own.

47:14.131 --> 47:19.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: He points to
efforts like the state's Forever
Wild Land Trust, as well as

47:19.437 --> 47:25.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to local agencies like the
Mobile Bay Estuaries Program,
which in this large subdivision
has

47:25.643 --> 47:30.881 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
been working to mitigate storm
water drainage problems caused
by poor planning in the 1970s.

47:30.881 --> 47:33.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERTA SWANN, Director, Mobile
Bay National Estuary Program:
You can't just go in and

47:33.117 --> 47:37.722 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
restore a stream. You have to
strengthen its ability to handle
those larger quantities

47:37.722 --> 47:39.623 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of storm water runoff.

47:39.623 --> 47:43.461 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Roberta Swann is
director of the estuaries
effort.

47:43.461 --> 47:48.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERTA SWANN: This is not a
natural stream restoration. This
is an enhanced stream
restoration.

47:48.466 --> 47:55.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are rocks in here that are
not native. And the reason why
it's not a true stream

47:55.072 --> 47:58.542 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
restoration is because we have
to accommodate the impacts of
humans on the environment.

47:58.542 --> 47:59.610 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
If we...

47:59.610 --> 48:01.445 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Because
that's inevitable.

48:01.445 --> 48:05.950 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERTA SWANN: It's inevitable.
And if we were to turn the delta
into a national park,

48:05.950 --> 48:10.488 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we would lose the ability to
mitigate the human impacts on
that ecosystem.

48:10.488 --> 48:14.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Agreement on the
need to protect a precious
natural resource, but vast
differences

48:14.658 --> 48:17.261 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on how to do it.

48:17.261 --> 48:20.164 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
E.O. WILSON: That was part of
the story of how many species
you can get packed into a

48:20.164 --> 48:20.765 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
small area.

48:20.765 --> 48:22.299 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BILL FINCH: Get packed in there.

48:22.299 --> 48:26.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Bill Finch and
Edward Wilson want to limit some
development, but see a

48:26.570 --> 48:32.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
potential compromise with
hunters and fishers in a
National Wildlife Refuge
designation

48:32.409 --> 48:35.412 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that would still allow
those sports to continue.

48:35.412 --> 48:39.850 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BILL FINCH: There are a lot of
options out there that we can
explore that allow us to

48:39.850 --> 48:46.090 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have it all in many ways, to do
the things we're doing now, to
have the kind of careful

48:46.090 --> 48:51.162 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
human use of the delta that we
have got now, but still preserve
our biodiversity.

48:51.162 --> 48:56.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And for Ed
Wilson, finding a way to protect
the delta of his youth is

48:56.066 --> 49:01.272 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
part of a much larger goal of
setting aside half the Earth for
habitat, one which begins

49:01.272 --> 49:04.108 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
with a lesson in humility.

49:04.108 --> 49:11.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
E.O. WILSON: There are about two
million species known worldwide
of all kinds of organisms.

49:11.982 --> 49:17.087 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the total number of species
is probably close to 10 million
worldwide, meaning we

49:17.087 --> 49:26.363 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have only discovered, much less
studied, about 20 percent of all
the species. So, here is

49:26.363 --> 49:31.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a world that is waiting for
exploration, and that's just the
beginning.

49:31.569 --> 49:41.378 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For the "PBS
NewsHour," I'm Jeffrey Brown in
the Mobile-Tensaw River Delta.

49:41.378 --> 49:53.390 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Remembrances
continued to pour in today for
singer and songwriter Prince,

49:53.390 --> 49:57.461 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
who died yesterday at
his home in Minnesota.

49:57.461 --> 50:00.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even President Obama paused to
reflect on the superstar's
legacy during his news
conference

50:00.898 --> 50:02.633 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in London.

50:02.633 --> 50:05.035 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States: He put out great
music and he was a great

50:05.035 --> 50:07.238 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
performer.

50:07.238 --> 50:12.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a remarkable loss. And I'm
staying at Winfield House, the
U.S. ambassador's residence.

50:12.176 --> 50:19.149 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It so happens our ambassador has
a turntable, and so this
morning, we played "Purple Rain"

50:19.149 --> 50:23.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and "Delirious" just to get
warmed up before we left the
house for important bilateral

50:23.387 --> 50:24.255 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
meetings like this.

50:24.255 --> 50:26.223 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

50:26.223 --> 50:30.427 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mr. Obama's
tribute was one of many from
friends and fans alike.

50:30.427 --> 50:34.698 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Here's a collection.

50:34.698 --> 50:41.171 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
From the New Orleans Superdome,
to San Francisco's City Hall,
landmarks across the country lit

50:41.171 --> 50:47.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up in Prince's signature color
purple last night to honor the
iconic musician. But, for

50:47.945 --> 50:54.451 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
many, remembering the superstar
meant celebrating the songs that
were his life's work.

50:54.451 --> 51:03.727 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Minnesota, thousands flooded
into downtown Minneapolis to
dance the night away outside

51:03.727 --> 51:10.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the nightclub where his movie
"Purple Rain" was filmed, while,
in New York, hundreds turned

51:10.000 --> 51:16.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out for a street party hosted by
filmmaker and Prince friend
Spike Lee.

51:16.707 --> 51:24.014 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Over on Broadway, tributes
flowed from fellow singers and
musicians. The cast of the smash

51:24.014 --> 51:31.255 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
hit "Hamilton" danced to
Prince's "Let's Go Crazy" after
their curtain call.

51:31.255 --> 51:36.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And at the nearby at the Bernard
B. Jacobs Theatre, actress
Jennifer Hudson led the cast

51:36.694 --> 51:48.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of "The Color Purple" in a
rendition of one of the singer's
most iconic melodies.

51:48.439 --> 51:53.344 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Prince died yesterday at age 57.

51:53.344 --> 51:57.114 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And the tributes go on.

51:57.114 --> 52:03.287 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On the "NewsHour" online: Spicy
fish with couscous and fried
zucchini with mint aren't

52:03.287 --> 52:08.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dishes normally associated with
Italian cuisine, but these
delicacies are quintessential
for

52:08.559 --> 52:14.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Roman Jews, who have lived in
the Italian capital for
centuries. As the holiday of
Passover

52:14.064 --> 52:18.836 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
begins tonight, we talked to the
authors of the new book "Tasting
Rome." They gave us

52:18.836 --> 52:22.373 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
two kosher recipes perfect
for a family celebration.

52:22.373 --> 52:27.778 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You can find them on our
home page, PBS.org/NewsHour.

52:27.778 --> 52:32.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a reminder about some
upcoming programs from our PBS
colleagues. Later tonight on

52:32.649 --> 52:37.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"Washington Week": Republicans
prepare for a brokered
convention, President Obama
repairs

52:37.621 --> 52:45.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
relations with Saudi Arabia, and
female faces are coming to U.S.
paper bills.

52:45.195 --> 52:50.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On "PBS NewsHour" Saturday:
Local governments and private
industry are striking deals to

52:50.467 --> 52:55.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
get infrastructure projects
under way. But are they a good
deal for taxpayers? Hear more

52:55.873 --> 53:00.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from Virginia's Governor Terry
McAuliffe on one such deal in
his state. That's tomorrow

53:00.044 --> 53:03.881 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on "PBS NewsHour Weekend."

53:03.881 --> 53:08.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we will be back right here
on Monday with a look at how
Nepal is coping one year after

53:08.318 --> 53:10.621 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a devastating earthquake.

53:10.621 --> 53:13.557 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
